{
  "texts": [
    "For instance, bit error probability (BEP) approximations using the Q-function are derived in [4], [5], which is valid only for large sample sizes, while [5], [6] extended this to a non-coherent TNM system under Rayleigh fading channels.",
    "However, these approximations introduce significant inaccuracies in threshold detection, BEP calculation, and their optimization, particularly for practical sample counts.",
    "This occurs since the Gaussian assumption in those works neglects the chisquared nature of the variance estimator, leading to suboptimal results and unreliable performance predictions.",
    "In [7], a maximum likelihood detector is used to calculate the optimal threshold value for detection under constant static channels, and a closed-form BEP expression is derived considering a binary modulated thermal noise communication (TNC) system.",
    "Despite recent studies on TNM, existing works lack rigorous analysis of their behavior and parameter trade-offs under realistic fading conditions, such as Rician channels, which encompass both line-of-sight (LoS) and scattered components.In this context, for the first time and aligned with the stringent power constraints of IoT, 5G, and 6G networks, we characterize binary TNC systems under Rician fading channels."
  ]
}